nondisjunction","Balanced Robertsonian translocation in the father","Mitotic nondisjunction causing mosaicism","De novo isochromosome formation","Partial deletion of chromosome 21"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case describes \u003Cstrong\u003Ebalanced Robertsonian translocation in the father\u003C/strong\u003E. The child has 46 chromosomes, which rules out the typical trisomy 21 caused by meiotic nondisjunction leading to 47 chromosomes. The father\u0027s unusual karyotype indicates he is likely a balanced carrier.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPaternal meiotic nondisjunction\u003C/strong\u003E would result in 47 chromosomes in the child\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitotic nondisjunction causing mosaicism\u003C/strong\u003E would show varying cell lines with 46 and 47 chromosomes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDe novo isochromosome formation\u003C/strong\u003E is extremely rare and would typically show 47 chromosomes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPartial deletion of chromosome 21\u003C/strong\u003E would cause different clinical features than Down syndrome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERobertsonian translocations account for approximately 4% of Down syndrome cases. While carriers are phenotypically normal, they can pass extra chromosome 21 material to offspring, resulting in Down syndrome with 46 chromosomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDown syndrome is characterised by distinctive physical features including upslanting palpebral fissures, epicanthal folds, flat nasal bridge, small ears, protruding tongue, single palmar crease, hypotonia, and short stature. Associated medical conditions include congenital heart defects (particularly atrioventricular septal defects), gastrointestinal abnormalities, and increased risk of leukaemia. Intellectual disability is universal but varies in severity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Down syndrome can occur through three distinct genetic mechanisms: nondisjunction (95%), Robertsonian translocation (4%), and mosaicism (1%).","Robertsonian translocations in Down syndrome typically involve chromosome 21 and either chromosome 14 or another chromosome 21.","Down syndrome has characteristic physical features including upslanting palpebral fissures, flat nasal bridge, and single palmar crease."],"references":["Asim A, Kumar A, Muthuswamy S, Jain S, Agarwal S. \u201cDown syndrome: an insight of the disease\u201d. Journal of Biomedical Science. 2015;22(1):41. Available at: https://jbiomedsci.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12929-015-0138-y"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53519"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16898"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53519"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-08T21:06:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-08T21:06:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9588"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68062"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rel